## Cursor model switch guide (Ryan quick ref)

Standing advice ... not session-ephemeral. Start with **Grok** or **Composer**; switch when stuck or the job type changes.

### Quick pick

| Situation | Use |
| --- | --- |
| Ship a feature, fix a bug, deploy, update docs | **Grok** or **Composer 2.5** |
| Pure multi-file edits / “just change the code” | **Composer 2.5** |
| Hard architecture / subtle correctness / “why is this wrong?” | **Opus** |
| Balanced coding + reasoning, default daily driver | **Sonnet** |
| Product copy, UX wording, creative exploration | **Fable** |
| Structured analysis, tables, careful review | **Terra** |

### When to switch (one-liners)

- **Stay on Grok** when you want: find it → fix it → commit/push/deploy → update `WAKEUP` / backlog. Fast agent loops.
- **Switch to Composer 2.5** when the job is mostly mechanical repo surgery and you don’t need much product chat.
- **Switch to Opus** when you’re stuck after 1–2 attempts, the blast radius is scary, or the bug is “impossible” / cross-system.
- **Switch to Sonnet** when you want a steady middle ground: solid code + clear reasoning without Opus weight.
- **Switch to Fable** for voice, landing copy, bot persona wording, marketing-ish text.
- **Switch to Terra** for audits, checklists, migration inventories, “compare A vs B carefully.”

### EdgeTilt cheat sheet

| Task | Model |
| --- | --- |
| Bot portal UI, Lounge CSS, small Edge Function tweak | Grok / Composer |
| Scott odds / live poll / cron / SQL chain | Grok first; **Opus** if cron/RLS/Edge auth is cursed |
| X ingest / bearer / oEmbed weirdness | Grok |
| Freemium / RLS / entitlements design | **Opus** or Sonnet |
| AP guide copy / voice prompts | Fable or Grok |
| “Update all continuity docs” | Grok |
| Security / production cutover review | **Opus** (or Security Review subagent) |
| PR babysit / CI loop | Composer or Grok |

### Rule of thumb

1. Start with **Grok** or **Composer**.
2. If you’re spinning or the design has real tradeoffs → **Opus**.
3. If you need pretty words → **Fable**.
4. Don’t model-hop mid-tiny-fix unless you’re stuck.

